<p>Is there a type of story that is more suited on the stage (performance/plays/theater) than others?
This question previously had details. They are now in a comment.
Profile photo for Marcus Geduld
Marcus Geduld
, Published author, lifelong reader.
Answered Jan 12, 2014
Iâ€™m a theatre director, and I have three thoughts for you:</p>

<ol>
  <li>On stage, we can only observe behavior. We canâ€™t know whatâ€™s going on inside a characterâ€™s head (as we can in a novel or in a filmâ€™s dream sequence). We can only hear what he says and see what he does.</li>
</ol>

<p>Obviously, there are exceptions to this. Shakespeare wrote soliloquies, and Tennessee Williams used a narrator in â€œThe Glass Menagerie.â€ Doing either well is extremely hard, because narration and inner monologues are literary devices, not immediately at home on the stage. If you employ them without having the talent of a Shakespeare or Williams, you risk writing plays that seem as if they were poorly-adapted from novels.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s tough to tell an entire story with just behavior, because you need the audience to understand key plot information, and beginners often canâ€™t figure out ways to convey it without having a character simply tell it to the audience.</p>

<p>One failure is the non-theatrical, literary speech. The other way is to insert clunky exposition into dialogue: â€œHere it is, 1986, and youâ€™re wearing a fedora!â€ You need to find another way!</p>

<p>Read this: David Mamet on Dramatic Writing.</p>

<p>If you insist on narration or soliloquies, make sure the character wants something and is using his speech to try to get it. That (using words to get something) is a form of behavior. That is dramatic. In Shakespeareâ€™s most famous soliloquy, Hamlet is actively trying to figure out whether to kill himself or not. Heâ€™s not explaining plot the the audience.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s instructive to track Anton Chekhovâ€™s growth as a playwright. In his first major play, â€œThe Seagull,â€ he created a fairly naturalistic world. That is, in general, it doesnâ€™t break of the fourth wall. Except it doesâ€”awkwardlyâ€”a few times. Itâ€™s very odd. You feel like youâ€™re watching a play similar in style to something Ibsen might have written, but then, out of nowhere, a character starts talking to the audience. Or maybe heâ€™s just talking to himself â€¦ out loud â€¦ for a really long time. The young Chekhov simply couldnâ€™t figure out another way to structure his play.</p>

<p>Since heâ€™s Chekhov, the speeches themselves are fantastic, so itâ€™s almost forgivable, but it still feels as if heâ€™s mashed two types of drama together in an unholy union.</p>

<p>His next play, â€œUncle Vanya,â€ suffers from the same defect. Itâ€™s a brilliant play. One of the best ever written. But, again, itâ€™s basically naturalistic, except in two places where characters talk to â€¦ no one? â€¦ to the audience? Still, itâ€™s more skillful than â€œThe Seagull.â€ In this later play, the monologues happen when characters are extremely agitated, so itâ€™s sort of believable they might talk to themselves. Chekhov was clearly wrestling with the problem, trying to find ways to make these speeches plausible.</p>

<p>In his next play, â€œThe Three Sisters,â€ he figures it out! He comes up with dramatic excuses for characters to talk to themselves at length. In one case, itâ€™s because a character is drunk. Itâ€™s plausible, because drunk people sometimes think theyâ€™re in company when theyâ€™re alone. In another case, itâ€™s because a character is talking to someone else who is offstage.</p>

<p>In his final play, â€œThe Cherry Orchard,â€ Chekhov was able to completely dispense with soliloquies. He figured out how to tell an entire story using interactions between charactersâ€”using behavior. And then he died. Which sucks for those of us who love his plays, but itâ€™s kind of a neat ending.</p>

<ol>
  <li>In each moment, each character should want something and be trying to get it. His need for this â€œsomethingâ€ must be really strong and there are only two possible reasons he doesnâ€™t immediately grab it: external obstacles and internal obstacles. For instance, a prince might want to rescue a sleeping beauty but be thwarted by a thicket of thorn bushes in his path. Thatâ€™s an external obstacle. If fear hiders him, thatâ€™s an internal obstacle.</li>
</ol>

<p>Every single thing a character does and says should be an attempt to overcome an obstacle in pursuit of his goal. If not, itâ€™s undramatic. Which is why exposition is a no-no. â€œMaking sure an the audience understands a plot pointâ€ is not a tactic that will get the character closer to his goal.</p>

<p>A major bug in plays by inexperienced writers is what I call â€œthe debate scene.â€ It usually means the writer is more concerned with an idea than with character. You can certainly express ideas with plays, but you must make them organic to the characters.</p>

<p>Or it means heâ€™s painted his characters into corners where they have goals but no possible options for achieving them. If your goal is to get me to give you a dollar and Iâ€™ve let you know thereâ€™s no way Iâ€™ll ever do this under any circumstances, itâ€™s not an interesting scene if you just keep saying â€œCome on! Give me a dollar!â€ over and over. If I simply wonâ€™t give it to you, Iâ€™ve won and youâ€™ve lost, and the scene should either be over or you should have a new goal: maybe stealing the candy bar you were going buy with my dollar.</p>

<p>In debate scenes, two characters argue for pages and pages. Neither seems to really be pursuing a goal, aside from maybe trying to convince the other of some intellectual point. And when itâ€™s clear thatâ€™s not working, the characters donâ€™t give up or switch tactics, they just keep on debating. At his worst, Shaw writes this way.</p>

<p>For an other example, read the end of â€œMedea.â€ Iâ€™m currently working on a production, and I wouldnâ€™t be bothering with it if I didnâ€™t think it was a great play, but it suffers at the end by turning a little debate-ish. Which makes it hard to stage without boring the audience.</p>

<p>Iâ€™m going to quote* at length, because I want you to see what Iâ€™m talking about. The following occurs after all the main action of the play has concluded. [Spoiler:] Medea has triumphed over Jason by killing their children, as well as killing his bride. Heâ€™s totally screwed. And he canâ€™t even take revenge, because sheâ€™s floating above him in a magic chariot. He canâ€™t reach her. There is nothing he can do. He know it; she knows it. Sheâ€™s won. Heâ€™s lost. The end â€¦ except not:</p>

<p>MEDEA
Your sons are dead. How does that feel?</p>

<p>JASON
They live on as spirits, who will haunt you to Hell.</p>

<p>MEDEA
The heavens know who started this.</p>

<p>JASON
They know your evil heart.</p>

<p>MEDEA
Hate on! I am so sick of your pathetic voice.</p>

<p>JASON
And I am heart-sick of yours. I would never hear it again.</p>

<p>MEDEA
Willingly. What are your last words to me?</p>

<p>JASON
Allow me my dead childrenâ€”
to bury them in peace, and mourn them.</p>

<p>MEDEA
No. I will bury them myself. â€¦</p>

<p>JASON
Then I call on the Fury of vengeance,
and the agents of Justice, to cut you down.</p>

<p>MEDEA
What god or higher power would listen to an oath-breaker and liar?</p>

<p>JASON
Filth! Child-murderer!</p>

<p>MEDEA
Go back and bury your bride.</p>

<p>JASON
I came here a father, and go home childless.</p>

<p>MEDEA
Your grief is just beginning. Wait until youâ€™re old.</p>

<p>JASON
Oh my children, dear sons.</p>

<p>MEDEA
Dear to their mother, not to you.</p>

<p>JASON
So dear you killed them?</p>

<p>MEDEA
That you might die of grief.</p>

<p>JASON
Let me just touch them once more:
hold them in my arms and kiss them one last time.</p>

<p>MEDEA
You rejected them, sent them into exile,
and now you want their kisses?</p>

<p>JASON
One last time â€¦</p>

<p>MEDEA
No. You waste your breath.</p>

<p>It kind of feels like this could go on forever. It could last for another few lines or another few hundred. Thereâ€™s no forward momentum. Medeaâ€™s goal is to make Jason suffer, but sheâ€™s already achieved that. â€œMaking him suffer moreâ€ isnâ€™t an interesting dramatic goal, because it doesnâ€™t up the ante of the last goal. Itâ€™s just the same goal all over again.</p>

<p>And aside from a few lines in which Jason asks to hold his dead childrenâ€”which heâ€™s already tried without successâ€”heâ€™s not really doing anything except saying forms of â€œI hate you.â€</p>

<p>Itâ€™s very hard for actors to make stagnant scenes like this work, but if they canâ€™t overcome the playwrightâ€™s blunder, the audience will start shifting in their seats. So donâ€™t write debate scenes!</p>

<p>Contrast the above with this scene from Shakespeareâ€™s â€œRichard III,â€ in which Lady Anne is pointing a sword Glouchester, who murdered her husband.</p>

<p>He lays his breast open: she offers [points] at it with his sword</p>

<p>GLOUCHESTER
Nay, do not pause; for I did kill King Henry,
But â€˜twas thy beauty that provoked me.
Nay, now dispatch; â€˜twas I that stabbâ€™d young Edward,
But â€˜twas thy heavenly face that set me on.</p>

<p>Here she lets fall the sword</p>

<p>Take up the sword again, or take up me.</p>

<p>LADY ANNE
Arise, dissembler: though I wish thy death,
I will not be the executioner.</p>

<p>GLOUCESTER
Then bid me kill myself, and I will do it.</p>

<p>LADY ANNE
I have already.</p>

<p>GLOUCESTER
Tush, that was in thy rage:
Speak it again, and, even with the word,
That hand, which, for thy love, did kill thy love,
Shall, for thy love, kill a far truer love;
To both their deaths thou shalt be accessary.</p>

<p>LADY ANNE
I would I knew thy heart.</p>

<p>GLOUCESTER
â€˜Tis figured in my tongue.</p>

<p>LADY ANNE
I fear me both are false.</p>

<p>GLOUCESTER
Then never man was true.</p>

<p>LADY ANNE
Well, well, put up your sword.</p>

<p>Here, Gloucester has a goal, which is to stop Lady Anne from fighting with him and agree to be his lover. She wants him dead, but internal obstacles (cowardliness) are stopping her from killing him. He understands her weakness and is exploiting it. This is forward momentum. This is actable.</p>

<p>For more information about goal-based dramatic writing, see the following books, which are for actors, not writers, but that doesnâ€™t matter. Theyâ€™re awesome for dramatists, too:</p>

<p>Amazon.com: A Practical Handbook for the Actor (Vintage) eBook: Melissa Bruder, David Mamet: Books</p>

