<ol>
  <li>If you think of each narrative medium (books, films, plays, etc) as a series of attempts to describe whatâ€™s happening in fictional worlds, youâ€™ll note that each can display some aspects of those worlds more easily than others.</li>
</ol>

<p>For instance, a historical novel has to waste thousands of words trying to evoke a Victorian dining room, whereas a film can do that instantly with an image. Films, on the other hand, have a hard time conveying charactersâ€™ thoughts, whereas a novel can do that effortlessly.</p>

<p>Hereâ€™s the twist: each medium is at its strongest when it evokes what it has the hardest time evoking.</p>

<p>Iâ€™m sure thatâ€™s confusing, so let me illustrate with radio plays. What does the radio play have a hard time evoking? Images! It has to do all its storytelling with sounds. When I was younger, I wanted to write and direct radio plays, and I wrongly thought the best stories for radio were ones in which images werenâ€™t important. So I came up with ideas like plays that were just phone conversations.</p>

<p>Then, one day, I heard a science fiction radio play in which a character said, â€œOh my God! Look at the size of that ship!â€</p>

<p>And it blew my mind. I realized it was the perfect line for a radio play. It evoked an image in a non-imagistic medium. If felt like magic, because â€œyou canâ€™t see things on the radio.â€ And yet it made me see something. That single line evoked a bigger space ship than the one at the end of â€œClose Encounters of the Third Kind.â€</p>

<p>In film, the most powerful moments are implied by cuts. We canâ€™t get inside the characterâ€™s head, but we can see a shot of him staring at something. Then we can cut to what heâ€™s looking at: a girl in a bikini. As if by magic, the film evokes lustâ€”an internal state, something it canâ€™t literally show.</p>

<p>In a play, the magic happens when you evoke the stuff plays canâ€™t literally display (without being clunky). The two main ones being inner psychology and offstage action.</p>

<p>Please read that last paragraph while keeping in mind my first two numbered points, above. Iâ€™m not suggesting you write a monologue in which a character explains what heâ€™s thinking. Iâ€™m suggesting that by watching his behavior we should come to understand what heâ€™s thinking.</p>

<p>And Iâ€™m also not suggesting a messenger should run on and describe the battle happening in the wings. Iâ€™m suggesting behavior should evoke an world beyond the stageâ€™s boundaries, as in â€œThe Three Sistersâ€ when characters long to go to Moscow.</p>

<p>The essence of dramatic form is to let an idea come over people without it being plainly stated. When you say something directly, itâ€™s simply not as potent as it is when you allow people to discover it for themselves.</p>

<p>â€“ Stanley Kubrick</p>

<p>The most powerful aspect of the â€œMona Lisaâ€ is the thing sheâ€™s smiling about. How did da Vinci paint that?</p>

